# Purpose

This rule governs how a manuscript that targets a Microchip microcontroller communicating over (or simulating) the CAN protocol is added to, organised in, and extended within this repository.
It complements `latex-inst.mdc` (which governs writing voice and ethics) and is triggered whenever work is performed inside `CAN_lab.X/paper/`.

Two invariants hold for every paper under `CAN_lab.X/paper/`:

1. The target is a **Microchip MCU** (PIC18, PIC24, dsPIC33, PIC32CM, PIC32MX/MZ/MK, SAM-family ARM, AVR-DA, or any future Microchip part).
2. The **CAN protocol** is the subject or the communication substrate of the work, whether realised on a built-in CAN controller, on an external MCP2515 / MCP25625, on a software simulation, or on a CAN transceiver-only educational board such as APP-MASTERS25-1 with ATA6561.

The chip family and the CAN application (gateway, diagnostics, body-electronics, motor control, telemetry dashboard, educational simulator) are free parameters and are selected per paper.

Follow this rule whenever a new topic is proposed, a new paper is scaffolded, or an existing paper is migrated.
Deviations must be called out in the plan file before the deviation is executed.

# Rule precedence

When guidance from multiple sources collides, precedence resolves in this order:

1. The MDPI journal template (for example `Definitions/mdpi.cls`) controls structural tokens such as `\authorcontributions{}` and `\conflictsofinterest{}`; their exact form matches the template verbatim.
2. This rule (`microchip-can-paper-workflow.mdc`) controls folder layout, slug convention, label prefixes, figure manifests, acronym discipline, and the ethics-block templates below.
3. `latex-inst.mdc` controls prose voice, forbidden words, paragraph rhythm, and the pre-commit writing checklist.
4. `swt-citation-policy.mdc` controls the SWT self-citation source-of-truth contract, the exact-three rule, the retraction block, editorial rules 3--7, the per-paper `swt-citation-summary.txt` artifact, and the five-check pre-commit verification snippet.

Any deviation from a higher-priority rule must be documented in the plan file before execution and, if repeated across topics, promoted into a rule amendment.

# Canonical folder layout

Every Microchip + CAN paper lives in its own folder under `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/`.
The layout is flat; no `eng/` or journal-specific subfolder is permitted (see "Hard-forbid of journal-named subfolders" below).
Each paper folder must contain, at minimum:

```
CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/
  main.tex
  figures/
    README.md
    manifest.md
  scripts/
    README.md
  review/
    README.md
```

An optional-but-recommended `hardware/` folder holds the artefacts that are unique to embedded work and that would not appear in a pure-software paper:

```
CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/
  hardware/
    README.md
    pinmap.md          # board-to-MCU pin assignments
    mcc_export/        # MCC Melody project snapshot, if reproducibility is claimed
    schematics/        # board schematic excerpts in PDF or SVG
    captures/          # oscilloscope, logic-analyser, CAN-bus log exports
```

`figures/`, `scripts/`, and `review/` are always created up front, even when empty, so the structure is identical across all topics and a reviewer never has to ask where a figure source lives.
`hardware/` is created the moment the paper cites any pin assignment, MCC setting, or captured waveform that a reviewer would want to audit.

# Slug naming rule

The folder name is derived mechanically from `\Title{}` so the slug is reproducible from the title alone and carries no author judgement.

## Core rule

Take the first six whitespace-separated tokens of `\Title{}`, lowercase them, and join them with a single underscore (`_`).
No token is paraphrased, skipped, or abbreviated; no character inside a token is dropped except where the normalisation table below explicitly allows it.

Worked example:

- `\Title{Real-Time Vehicle Telemetry Display System Based on CAN Protocol: A Hardware-Software Co-Design Approach Using Microchip PIC32CM Series}`
- Tokens 1--6: `Real-Time`, `Vehicle`, `Telemetry`, `Display`, `System`, `Based`
- Slug: `real-time_vehicle_telemetry_display_system_based`

## Character normalisation table

This is the only permitted normalisation.
Any character not covered here must be resolved by rewording the title before the folder is created, not by ad-hoc edits to the slug.

| Source pattern               | Slug form                                         | Rationale                                                         |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |
| LaTeX `--` (en-dash)         | `-` (single hyphen)                               | Filesystem portability across macOS, Linux, and Windows.          |
| Trailing `:` `;` `,` `.` `!` | stripped                                          | Title punctuation is grammatical, not identifying.                |
| Leading `"`, trailing `"`    | stripped                                          | Titles occasionally quote a concept; the quotes are decorative.   |
| `'` (apostrophe inside word) | stripped, preserving letters                      | Natural folder-typing expectations (`don't` -> `dont`).           |
| `(` `)` `[` `]`              | stripped                                          | Parenthetical titles collapse cleanly.                            |
| `&`                          | `and`                                             | Mirrors common English expansion.                                 |
| `/`                          | `-`                                               | Filesystem-reserved character replaced with a hyphen.             |
| Non-ASCII letter             | ASCII transliteration (`é` -> `e`, `ö` -> `o`)    | ASCII-only folder names.                                          |
| Numeric tokens               | kept as-is                                        | Numbers carry meaning in titles (part numbers, bus speeds, years). |

## Freeze-on-creation

The slug is frozen at the moment the folder is created.
Later edits to `\Title{}` do not trigger a folder rename.
If the title is revised so heavily that the slug becomes misleading, treat the revision as a new manuscript and create a new slug folder, citing the previous manuscript via `\cite{...}`.

## Collision resolution

If two papers would yield the same slug, append `_pt2` to the younger one.
This is the only allowed deviation from the six-word rule and must be recorded in the slug registry with a note.

## Grandfathered exceptions

Folders that predate this rule are retained under their original names and flagged in the slug registry under the `Note` column with the string `grandfathered (<N>-token)`.
Grandfathered slugs are not re-derived from their titles; they keep their pre-rule form to avoid breaking downstream references, and the `Note` column preserves the audit trail.
The six-token core rule applies to every new slug created after this rule takes effect.

The long human-readable title always lives inside `main.tex` under `\Title{...}` and is independent of the slug.

