# 10-step checklist for adding a new topic

1. Derive the slug mechanically from the candidate `\Title{}` using the core rule and the normalisation table.
2. Confirm the slug is not already taken under `CAN_lab.X/paper/` and append a new row to the slug registry above.
3. Create `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/` together with the four mandatory subpaths listed in the layout section, each seeded with a one-line `README.md`.
4. Copy the MDPI preamble (see the preamble spec below) into a fresh `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/main.tex`; do not copy body text from any sibling paper.
5. Fill `\Title{...}`, `\Author{...}`, `\abstract{...}`, and `\keyword{...}` with topic-specific content written from scratch.
6. Draft the section skeleton as described in `latex-inst.mdc`, ensuring all labels follow the canonical convention below.
7. List every planned figure in `figures/manifest.md` before producing the figure; the manifest entry comes first, the figure artifact second.
8. Place figure-generation scripts in `scripts/` with a `README.md` entry explaining their inputs, outputs, and runtime assumptions.
9. Run the firmware-source hygiene sweep (verify every cited pin, peripheral, register, or register-field in `main.tex` resolves against `src/main.c` or the cited MCC export), the label / bibliography hygiene check, the forbidden-word sweep defined in `latex-inst.mdc` against the new `main.tex`, and the SWT five-check pre-commit verification snippet from `swt-citation-policy.mdc` against every `CAN_lab.X/paper/*/main.tex` and the corresponding `swt-citation-summary.txt` files.
10. Commit using the convention `paper(<slug>): <imperative summary>`.

# MDPI preamble spec

Every `main.tex` begins with the MDPI `eng` document class, even if the target journal differs, because the Overleaf project hosting this repository is configured against the MDPI template bundle.
The following preamble block is the canonical seed and must remain syntactically identical across all papers; topic-specific packages are appended below this block, not interleaved within it.

```
\documentclass[eng,article,submit,pngtex,moreauthors]{Definitions/mdpi}
\firstpage{1}
\makeatletter
\setcounter{page}{\@firstpage}
\makeatother
\pubvolume{1}
\issuenum{1}
\articlenumber{0}
\pubyear{2026}
\copyrightyear{2026}
\datereceived{}
\dateaccepted{}
\datepublished{}
\hreflink{}
\Title{<SLUG-SPECIFIC TITLE>}
\TitleCitation{<SHORT CITATION TITLE>}
\Author{<AUTHORS>}
\AuthorCitation{<SHORT CITATION AUTHORS>}
\address{<AFFILIATIONS>}
\corres{Correspondence: <email>}
\abstract{<ABSTRACT, one sentence per line>}
\keyword{<semicolon-separated keyword list>}
\begin{document}
```

Topic-specific packages, `\newcommand` definitions, and macros may be added after `\begin{document}` only if they are also added in a commented block above `\begin{document}` for readability.

# Hard-forbid of journal-named subfolders

No paper folder may contain an `eng/`, `sensors/`, `applsci/`, `electronics/`, or similar journal-named subfolder.
If a submission requires a journal-specific variant of `main.tex`, the variant lives alongside `main.tex` with an underscore suffix (for example `main_electronics.tex`) and is declared in a new section of this rule before the variant is committed.

# Canonical `\label{}` convention

Labels exist so cross-references survive refactors.
The following prefixes are mandatory; inventing new prefixes is not permitted.

| Element            | Prefix   | Example                              |
| ------------------ | -------- | ------------------------------------ |
| Section            | `sec:`   | `\label{sec:intro}`                  |
| Subsection         | `sec:`   | `\label{sec:methods-can-frame}`      |
| Figure             | `fig:`   | `\label{fig:block-diagram}`          |
| Table              | `tab:`   | `\label{tab:pinmap}`                 |
| Algorithm          | `alg:`   | `\label{alg:crc15}`                  |
| Equation           | `eq:`    | `\label{eq:baud-timing}`             |
| Listing            | `lst:`   | `\label{lst:can-tx-routine}`         |
| Bibliography entry | (none)   | `\bibitem[...]{AuthorYear}`          |

Slugs inside labels use the same kebab-case convention as folder slugs.
Never use spaces, Unicode punctuation, or uppercase in a label body.
The `lst:` prefix is reserved for `\begin{lstlisting}` blocks; firmware snippets are common in this repository's genres and deserve their own namespace so cross-references to code remain distinguishable from figures and tables.

# Label and bibliography hygiene

Before committing an edit that changes labels or references, all four conditions below must hold.

1. Every `\label{...}` in `main.tex` is referenced by at least one `\ref{...}`, `\autoref{...}`, `\cref{...}`, or `\eqref{...}`.
2. Every `\ref{...}`, `\autoref{...}`, `\cref{...}`, or `\eqref{...}` target resolves to an existing `\label{...}`.
3. Every `\cite{...}` target resolves to an existing `\bibitem`.
4. Every `\bibitem` is cited at least once.

Reference shell snippet (run from the repository root, substituting the slug):

```bash
f="CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/main.tex"
grep -oE '\\label\{[^}]+\}'      "$f" | sort -u > /tmp/labels.txt
grep -oE '\\(ref|autoref|cref|eqref)\{[^}]+\}' "$f" | sort -u > /tmp/refs.txt
grep -oE '\\cite\{[^}]+\}'       "$f" | sort -u > /tmp/cites.txt
grep -oE '\\bibitem(\[[^]]*\])?\{[^}]+\}' "$f" | sort -u > /tmp/bibitems.txt
diff /tmp/labels.txt /tmp/refs.txt      # expect: every label used
diff /tmp/cites.txt  /tmp/bibitems.txt  # expect: every cite resolves
```

# `figures/manifest.md` requirement

Every paper folder carries a `figures/manifest.md` that is the single source of truth for all figures in the manuscript.
The file is a markdown table with exactly these columns:

```
| # | Filename | Label | Generator script | Caption summary | Regeneration command |
```

Each row corresponds to one figure.
If a figure is still planned but not yet produced, the row is included with `(planned)` in the filename column; this forces every figure to be declared before it is drawn.
Whenever a figure is added, renamed, or regenerated, the manifest row is edited in the same change.
The `Filename` column is a bare `.png` filename (see the PNG-only rule below); no paired `.pdf` partner is listed.

# Figures-folder cleanliness

- The `figures/` folder contains only `README.md`, `manifest.md`, and `.png` files. No other file extensions are permitted (no `.pdf`, `.svg`, `.eps`, `.json`, `.csv`, or raw data exports).
- Every `.png` under `figures/` appears in exactly one non-`(planned)` row of `manifest.md`; every non-`(planned)` manifest row points at a `.png` file that exists on disk.
- Figure-generator sidecar files (`.json` quantitative summaries, raw traces, intermediate CSVs, fixture files) live next to the generator under `scripts/`, never under `figures/`. The manuscript cites summary numbers via the `scripts/<name>.json` path, not a path inside `figures/`.
- Orphan artifacts are either promoted to the manifest or deleted; they are never left undocumented.

# Figure-script originality discipline

When two or more papers in this repository share figure-script authors, cross-paper scripts must not converge on a common visual style.
The same author naturally re-applies the same helpers, palette, and layout idiom; the result is a visually uniform series that reviewers and integrity tooling can correctly flag as common authorship and that reduces the perceived independence of the contributions.
Each new paper re-derives its figure-generation code along all six axes below.

| # | Axis                | Requirement                                                                                          |
| - | ------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1 | Helper function names | Rename paper-to-paper (for example `box()` vs. `draw_block()`); do not share names across siblings. |
| 2 | Colour constants    | Distinct hex codes per paper; no import of a shared palette module.                                  |
| 3 | Dash patterns       | Each paper picks one dash tuple (for example `(0, (5, 4))` vs. `(0, (6, 3))`) and holds it.          |
| 4 | Font family         | Distinct `font.family` across siblings (for example `DejaVu Sans` vs. `DejaVu Serif`).               |
| 5 | Callout style       | Distinct visual vocabulary (numbered circles vs. diamond badges vs. letter tags).                    |
| 6 | Layout idiom        | Distinct structural approach (imperative `box(x, y, w, h)` sequence vs. coordinate-grid dict vs. `PathPatch` with Bezier curves). |

Reuse by Python import across sibling papers is not permitted; parallel re-derivation is required.
Shared utilities that would produce identical output (for example a single `palette.py` imported by every paper) are considered a figure-script originality violation.
The sweep for this rule is a `diff` of any two sibling `scripts/*.py` files for: helper function signatures, RGB/HEX constants, dash-pattern literals, `font.family` strings, and the structural pattern of the main plotting function.

Embedded-domain specifics: block diagrams, pin maps, and CAN-frame bit-layout diagrams are all prone to cross-paper convergence because the underlying graphical vocabulary (rectangles, arrows, bit-ticks) is small.
A sibling-safe way to honour axis 6 in this domain is to pick one structural idiom per paper and hold it: for example, one paper draws the block diagram with imperative `ax.add_patch(Rectangle(...))` calls, the next uses a coordinate-grid dictionary fed to a helper that walks the grid, and a third composes the diagram from `PathPatch` with Bezier-curved signal routes.

# Acronym discipline

- First use in the abstract: spell-out plus parenthetical acronym, for example `Controller Area Network (CAN)`.
- First use in the body (independent of the abstract): repeat the spell-out plus parenthetical acronym.
- Subsequent uses: acronym only.
- Acronyms introduced in a section and not used again are replaced by the spell-out.

Seed list of acronyms that recur across this repository (the spell-out in the left column is the canonical expansion; the right column indicates whether the acronym is usually safe to use without expansion in an MDPI engineering venue):

| Acronym | Canonical spell-out                        | Expand on first use? |
| ------- | ------------------------------------------ | -------------------- |
| CAN     | Controller Area Network                    | Yes                  |
| CRC     | Cyclic Redundancy Check                    | Yes                  |
| DLC     | Data Length Code                           | Yes                  |
| SOF     | Start of Frame                             | Yes                  |
| EOF     | End of Frame                               | Yes                  |
| ACK     | Acknowledgement                            | Yes                  |
| ID      | Identifier                                 | No                   |
| MCU     | Microcontroller Unit                       | Yes                  |
| ADC     | Analog-to-Digital Converter                | Yes                  |
| UART    | Universal Asynchronous Receiver-Transmitter| Yes                  |
| I2C     | Inter-Integrated Circuit                   | Yes                  |
| SPI     | Serial Peripheral Interface                | Yes                  |
| MCC     | MPLAB Code Configurator                    | Yes                  |
| XC32    | Microchip XC32 compiler                    | Yes                  |
| GPIO    | General-Purpose Input/Output               | Yes                  |
| ISR     | Interrupt Service Routine                  | Yes                  |
| RTOS    | Real-Time Operating System                 | Yes                  |
| OBD-II  | On-Board Diagnostics, second generation    | Yes                  |
