The table is not exhaustive; additions are accepted via a one-line amendment to this rule when a new acronym is used across two or more papers.

# Canonical wording templates for mandatory MDPI blocks

To prevent paraphrasing drift across papers on a shared platform, the templates below are copy-paste seeds with one or two placeholder fields.
Alter the placeholders, not the surrounding phrasing, unless the project demands otherwise.

Papers in this repository do not involve human subjects by default; `\institutionalreview{}` and `\informedconsent{}` are therefore omitted from the canonical seed.
If a future paper introduces a human-factors study (for example, a driver-usability evaluation of a CAN dashboard), that paper proposes an amendment to this rule before re-introducing the human-subjects blocks.

```latex
\funding{This research received no external funding.}

\dataavailability{The firmware source, figure-generation scripts, hardware pin map, and captured CAN-bus or oscilloscope traces supporting the reported findings are included in the paper's repository folder under `src/`, `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/scripts/`, `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/hardware/pinmap.md`, and `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/hardware/captures/`, respectively. Public datasets and vendor datasheets are cited inline; derived artefacts are available from the corresponding author on reasonable request.}

\authorcontributions{Conceptualization, <initials>; methodology, <initials>; software, <initials>; validation, <initials>; formal analysis, <initials>; investigation, <initials>; resources, <initials>; data curation, <initials>; writing---original draft preparation, <initials>; writing---review and editing, <initials>; visualization, <initials>; supervision, <initials>; project administration, <initials>. All authors have read and agreed to the published version of the manuscript.}

\conflictsofinterest{The authors declare no conflicts of interest.}
```

# Citation-key convention

- Pattern: `<LeadAuthorSurname><Year>`.
- Four-digit year, no abbreviations.
- Multi-word surnames follow publication conventions (`de la Torre` -> `DelaTorre2025`).
- Suffix with `a`, `b`, `c` on collision within a year (`Smith2025a`, `Smith2025b`).
- Vendor documents (Microchip datasheets, application notes) use the pattern `Microchip<DocID>` (for example `MicrochipDS60001712`) so the citation key stays stable across edition revisions.
- ISO and SAE standards use the pattern `ISO<Number>` or `SAE<Number>` (for example `ISO11898`).

# Required pre-reads

Before drafting prose in a new topic, read:

- `src/main.c` for the reference firmware, including pin assignments, peripheral initialisation, and the CAN-frame construction routine that most papers will cite or extend.
- `README.md` for the board-to-MCU wiring table, the MCC Melody walkthrough, and the canonical list of controls (buttons, potentiometer, LEDs, OLED) that current papers reference.
- `claude.md` for the project's design notes and the authoritative explanation of which parts of the current codebase are real hardware, which are transceiver-only, and which are pure software simulation.
- Every existing `CAN_lab.X/paper/*/main.tex` in full for the phrasings already in use.

A paper that claims reproducibility against the firmware must cite the exact commit hash of `src/main.c` in its Methods section; the pre-reads above ensure the author has seen that firmware before the claim is made.

# Pre-submission readiness checklist

Separate from the writing checklist in `latex-inst.mdc`; covers metadata, scope disclosure, and firmware traceability specifically.

- `\Title{}`, `\TitleCitation{}`, `\Author{}`, `\AuthorCitation{}`, `\AuthorNames{}` populated.
- ORCID present for every author who has one.
- `\address{}`, `\corres{}` complete.
- `\funding{}`, `\dataavailability{}` present and match the templates above (or an approved deviation).
- `\authorcontributions{}` uses CRediT-style initials only.
- `\conflictsofinterest{}` present.
- Target Microchip part number stated in `\Title{}` or abstract (for example `PIC32CM3204GV00048`, `dsPIC33CH512MP508`, `SAM E70Q21B`).
- CAN protocol role stated in the abstract using one of the three canonical labels: **real CAN controller** (built-in or external MCP2515/MCP25625), **transceiver-only educational simulation** (as on the APP-MASTERS25-1 board with ATA6561), or **pure software simulation** (no transceiver, no bus).
- Bibliography non-fabrication audit performed (every `\bibitem` inspected against a DOI, arXiv URL, Microchip document ID, or ISO/SAE document number).
- Label / bibliography hygiene passes.
- Figures-folder cleanliness passes.

# Commit-message convention

`paper(<slug>): <imperative summary>` for any change that touches `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/**`.
The slug inside the scope matches the folder name exactly.

# Split-topic guidance

A topic is split into a new manuscript rather than grown further once any of these rule-of-thumb thresholds is crossed:

- Roughly 12,000 words in `main.tex`.
- Six or more figures declared in `manifest.md`.
- Methods section needing more than four subsections.

When the split happens, the new manuscript:

- Creates its own slug folder following the core rule and normalisation table.
- Copies only the MDPI preamble; body prose is drafted from scratch.
- Cites the parent manuscript via `\cite{...}` wherever the parent's methods are reused.
- Registers a new row in the slug registry and marks the relationship in its `review/README.md`.

# Cross-paper originality discipline

Before drafting any prose in `CAN_lab.X/paper/<slug>/main.tex`, read every other `CAN_lab.X/paper/*/main.tex` in this repository in full.
Take note of the argument structures, figure captions, and phrasings already in use.
Do not copy sentences between sibling manuscripts, even when the underlying method is shared; cite the sibling manuscript via `\cite{...}` and paraphrase at the argument level as defined in `latex-inst.mdc`.

When a technical component is genuinely shared (for example, the same CRC-15 implementation or the same MCC Melody peripheral configuration), the originality obligation is met by:

* writing a new introductory sentence that explains why the component is appropriate for the current topic,
* citing the sibling paper for the detailed derivation,
* restricting the current manuscript to the delta relative to the sibling treatment.

A ten-word consecutive overlap with any sibling `main.tex` is treated as self-plagiarism and must be rewritten from a different argument order, not by swapping synonyms.

## Symbol discipline across siblings

When a paper introduces a symbol that any sibling `main.tex` already binds to a different meaning, the new paper must do all three of the following:

1. Pick a visibly distinct symbol.
   Prefer a subscripted variant (for example `T_{bit,arb}` in an arbitration-phase paper when a sibling paper already uses `T_{bit}` for the single-phase nominal bit time).
   Never silently rebind the sibling's symbol.
2. Call out the disambiguation explicitly in the equation's introductory sentence, with wording such as "we use $T_{bit,arb}$ rather than the sibling's $T_{bit}$ to avoid conflating the arbitration-phase bit time with the nominal bit time".
3. Record the collision in the paper's `review/README.md` under a "Symbol collisions" section so downstream reviewers can audit it.

Symbol collisions are checked during the pre-commit sweep by grepping each new display equation's left-hand side against every sibling `main.tex`.

## Cross-paper citation placement

When a paper builds on a sibling's method, dataset pointer, firmware base, or captured bus log, the sibling is cited in two distinct places, not one:

1. In the Introduction where the method is first named.
2. In the Methods / Design / Evaluation section at the point of consumption.

Citing the sibling in only one of the two locations is treated as a hygiene failure during the pre-commit sweep.
The first citation positions the sibling for the reader; the second citation gives the reviewer a concrete anchor against which to check that the consuming paper has not silently redefined the shared component.

# Firmware / hardware replay protocol

When a paper re-uses a sibling's firmware, captured CAN-bus log, oscilloscope trace, or board configuration by citation rather than by re-implementation, the Evaluation section must contain a subsection titled `Firmware / hardware replay protocol` that states four items, in this order:

1. **Source of the replayed artefact.** Which sibling firmware commit, board revision, CAN-bus log, or oscilloscope capture is consumed, cited by `\cite{...}` and by the sibling's public pointer (for example `src/main.c@<commit>`, `CAN_lab.X/paper/<sibling-slug>/hardware/captures/<file>`) when one exists.
2. **Interface contract.** The CAN baud rate and bit-timing parameters, the CAN ID map with DLC for each identifier, the physical layer realisation (real controller, external MCP2515, transceiver-only educational board, or pure simulation), the MCU clock configuration, the voltage rails, and the board-to-MCU pin map; any conversion step between the sibling's export format (for example raw `asc` log, `blf`, `csv`, or `png` oscilloscope image) and the consuming paper's input format.
3. **What is held constant versus what is replayed.** Toolchain version (for example `XC32 v4.30`) and MCC Melody snapshot that are unchanged from the sibling; peripheral initialisation stages that are reused verbatim; application-layer logic that is re-executed on the replay; stages that are simulated or stubbed (for example a CRC-15 computation replacing a missing on-chip CAN controller).
4. **Failure modes.** Explicit behaviour if the sibling's contract changes (chip-revision drift, MCC regeneration differences between tool versions, ATA6561 swap for a different transceiver, loss of a specific board feature), so silent breakage does not occur when a sibling refactors its firmware or hardware baseline.

A paper that replays sibling firmware or captured bus data without a `Firmware / hardware replay protocol` subsection is considered incomplete under this rule and must be extended before pre-submission review.

# Paper-genre appendix

This repository currently admits three manuscript genres.
Each genre is associated with a required section template and a minimum content contract.
A paper that spans two genres (for example a hardware-software co-design system evaluated on a reproducibility harness) inherits the union of both contracts.

## Genre A: Hardware-software co-design system

Exemplar: `real_time_vehicle_telemetry_display`.

- **Required sections**: Introduction, Related Work, System Architecture (with subsections for Hardware Platform, Firmware Architecture, Peripheral Integration, CAN Frame Design), Implementation, Results, Discussion, Conclusion.
- **Minimum content**: 1 table (pin map or CAN ID map), 1 algorithm (for example a CRC-15 calculation or a frame-dispatch routine), 1 numbered equation (for example the bit-timing equation), 2 figures (at minimum one system block diagram and one CAN-frame layout diagram or a dashboard photograph).
- **Scope disclaimer**: frames the paper as "an engineering system demonstration, not a certified automotive product". The Discussion includes a validation-ladder table with an explicit out-of-scope row that names what would need to change for a certification-ready deployment (for example ISO 11898-1 conformance testing, functional-safety processes, EMC compliance).

## Genre B: Embedded protocol simulation / education tool

- **Required sections**: Introduction, Related Work, System Architecture, Protocol Model (with a CAN-frame structure subsection showing how SOF, ID, DLC, Data, CRC, and EOF are represented in firmware), Pedagogical or Functional Evaluation, Discussion, Conclusion.
- **Minimum content**: 2 tables (for example an acronym / CAN-field reference and a hardware pin map), 1 algorithm (the simulation loop or the CRC computation), 2 numbered equations (for example CRC polynomial and frame-timing approximation), 3 figures (architecture diagram, frame-bit layout, and a screen or OLED capture demonstrating the simulation).
- **Scope disclaimer**: frames the paper as "an educational simulator, not a conformance-certified CAN node". The Discussion includes an explicit paragraph stating which CAN-protocol features are simulated (for example arbitration, error frames, bit stuffing) and which are omitted, and names the transceiver-only or no-transceiver nature of the board.

## Genre C: Reproducibility harness / benchmark

- **Required sections**: Introduction, Related Work, Harness Design, Ground-Truth Model (hardware + firmware baseline captured by the harness), Replay Harness, Evaluation Strategy (with a `Firmware / hardware replay protocol` subsection, which is mandatory for this genre), Discussion, Conclusion.
- **Minimum content**: 2 tables, 1 algorithm, 3 numbered equations, 3 figures.
- **Scope disclaimer**: frames the paper as "an infrastructure contribution, not a fielded product". The Discussion includes an explicit section on how the harness's synthetic ground truth (for example CRC values computed in software without a real CAN controller observing the bus) differs from physical-layer ground truth captured on a certified bus analyser.

## Genre combination

A paper that satisfies more than one genre contract (for example a Genre A co-design system that ships with a Genre C replay harness) inherits the union of the section lists and the sum of the minimum content contracts.
The combined genre is recorded in the paper's `review/README.md` under a "Genre" line so that reviewers know which contracts apply.

# Extending the rule

When a genuinely new section type is introduced (for example, a new validation paradigm, a new protocol variant such as CAN FD or CAN XL, or a new family of Microchip parts with substantially different CAN peripherals), extend this rule rather than inventing a local convention inside a single `main.tex`.
Propose the extension in a plan file, then add it here so subsequent topics inherit the convention automatically.
